the "realistic utopias" of liberal theory strike many as wishful thinking. Can politics think utopia otherwise? Can utopian thinking contribute to the renewal of politics?In Political Uses of Utopia, an international cast of leading and emerging theorists agree that the uses of utopia for politics are multiple and nuanced and lie somewhere between—or, better yet, beyond—the mainstream caution against it and the conviction that another, better world ought to be possible. Representing a range of perspectives on the grand tradition of Western utopianism, which extends back half a millennium and perhaps as far as Plato, these essays are united in their interest in the relevance of utopianism to specific historical and contemporary political contexts. Featuring contributions from Miguel Abensour, Étienne Balibar, Raymond Geuss, and Jacques Rancière, among others, Political Uses of Utopia reopens the question of whether and how utopianism can inform political thinking and action today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aUtopiasxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh1 aAbensour, Miguel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalibar, Étienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuey, Francisco Fernández, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrostowska, S. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrostowska, S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischbach, Franck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeuss, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallward, Peter,